{{Refimprove|date=October 2018}} {{infobox nobility | name = Louis IV, Count Palatine of the Rhine | image = | caption = | noble family= [[House of Wittelsbach]] | father = [[Louis III, Elector Palatine]] | mother = [[Matilda of Savoy]] | spouse = [[Margaret of Savoy, Countess Palatine of the Rhine|Margarete of Savoy]] | issue = [[Philip, Elector Palatine]] | birth_date = 1 January 1424 | birth_place = [[Heidelberg]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1449|8|13|1424|1|1|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Worms, Germany|Worms]] | burial_place= [[Church of the Holy Spirit (Heidelberg)|Church of the Holy Spirit]] in [[Heidelberg]] }} '''Louis IV, Count Palatine of the Rhine''' (1 January 1424, [[Heidelberg]] &ndash; 13 August 1449, [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]) was an [[Elector Palatine]] of the [[Rhine]] from the [[House of Wittelsbach]] in 1436 - 1449.
==Biography== Louis IV was the son of [[Louis III, Elector Palatine]] and his second wife [[Matilda of Savoy]]. His mother was a fourth-generation descendant of [[Thomas III of Piedmont]] (1248 - 1282), the eldest son of [[Thomas II of Savoy]].
From the death of Louis III in 1436 until 1442, Louis IV ruled under guardianship of his uncle, Count Palatine [[Otto I, Count Palatine of Mosbach|Otto I of Mosbach]]. In 1444 he repelled the attacks of the [[Armagnac (party)|Armagnacs]] as an Imperial captain.
In 1445 he married [[Margaret of Savoy, Countess Palatine of the Rhine|Margarete of Savoy]],{{sfn|Kekewich|2008|p=214}} widow of king [[Louis III of Naples]] and daughter of Duke [[Amadeus VIII of Savoy]]. With her, he had his only son, [[Philipp of the Rhine|Philipp]] (14 July 1448 &ndash; 28 February 1508). When he died in 1449, aged 25 years, in Worms, his brother [[Frederick I, Elector Palatine|Frederick]] inherited the Palatinate. Louis was buried in the [[Holy Spirit]] church of Heidelberg.
