{{Orphan|date=August 2017}}
'''Operation Legacy''' was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Colonial Office]] (later [[Foreign Office]]) program to destroy or hide files, to prevent them being inherited by its ex-colonies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2016/11/british-empire-kenya-oman-ireland-state-secrecy/|title=Erasing Empire - Jacobin|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=yauZDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT131&lpg=PT131&dq=operation%20legacy%20%20empire&source=bl&ots=0U62BcKtrP&sig=ayvQMyZE9ZSz3rbnVyupUZ-xp0I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjs4YuB76PQAhVLK8AKHXxpAXAQ6AEIOzAE#v=onepage&q=operation%20legacy%20%20empire&f=false|title=The History Thieves: Secrets, Lies and the Shaping of a Modern Nation|first=Ian|last=Cobain|date=1 September 2016|publisher=Granta Publications|via=Google Books}}</ref> It ran from the 1950s until the 1970s, when the [[decolonisation]] of the [[British Empire]] was at its height.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.warhistoryonline.com/war-articles/operation-legacy-britain-destroyed-thousands-colonial-files.html|title=Operation Legacy: How Britain Destroyed Thousands Of Colonial Files|date=9 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
As decolonisation progressed, British officials were keen to avoid a repeat of the embarrassment that had been caused by the overt burning of documents that took place in Delhi in 1947, which had been covered by local Indian news sources. On May 3, 1961, Iain Macleod from the UK Colonial Office, wrote a telegram to all British embassies to advise them on the best way to retrieve and dispose of sensitive documents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.warhistoryonline.com/war-articles/operation-legacy-britain-destroyed-thousands-colonial-files.html|title=Operation Legacy: How Britain Destroyed Thousands Of Colonial Files|last=Winston|first=George|date=2014-01-09|work=WAR HISTORY ONLINE|access-date=2017-07-26|language=en-US}}</ref>
All secret documents in the colonial administrations were vetted by [[MI5]] or [[Special Branch]] agents to ensure those that might embarrass the British government or show racial or religious bias, were destroyed or sent to the United Kingdom.<ref name="independent.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/revealed-how-british-empire-s-dirty-secrets-went-up-in-smoke-in-the-colonies-8971217.html|title=Revealed: How British Empire’s dirty secrets went up in smoke in the|date=29 November 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Precise instructions were given for methods to be used for destruction, including burning and dumping at sea.<ref name="independent.co.uk" /> Some of the files detailed torture methods used against opponents of the colonial administrations, ''e.g.'', during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/apr/18/britain-destroyed-records-colonial-crimes|title=Britain destroyed records of colonial crimes|first1=Ian|last1=Cobain|first2=Owen|last2=Bowcott|first3=Richard|last3=Norton-Taylor|date=17 April 2012|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>
Academic study of the end of the British Empire has been assisted in recent years by the declassification of the ''migrated archives'' in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) 141 series. After the UK government admitted in 2011 that it had secret documents related to the [[Mau Mau Uprising|Mau Mau]] case, it began to declassify documents and by November 2013 some 20,000 files had been declassified. These documents can now be accessed at the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|National Archives]] in Kew, London.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sato|first=Shohei|date=2017-04-11|title=‘Operation Legacy’: Britain’s Destruction and Concealment of Colonial Records Worldwide|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/03086534.2017.1294256|journal=The Journal of Imperial and Commonwealth History|volume=0|issue=0|pages=1–23|doi=10.1080/03086534.2017.1294256|issn=0308-6534}}</ref>
